❤️ Red Hot 💔
-
🥊 I started by lifting her hair in hopes of going violet red. After I lifted her hair and checked the bottom pieces, her hair began smoking and got extremely hot. (It turns out a previous stylist at a different salon put henna in her hair without her permission) We immediately rinsed, did the Extreme Cat treatment, and had to switch our plan for our color formula since we couldn’t use anything with high developers. We also had to cut most of her ends off because the chemical reaction caused them to fall out.
-
Long story short, if your gut isn’t good about your stylist, you’re most likely right about that feeling. We got lucky that we could  salvage what we could and the color turned out beautiful.

TRANSPARENCY

I have known for a long time that I wanted more than a job.  I wanted more than a career, just because I personally always wanted to help people. Clearly, sometimes having “jobs” helping people means you’re most likely not going to make a lot of money. Yes, doctors, lawyers... make more, but that was never my calling.

At the age of 16/17 my parents had a very successful business in which they wanted me to take part - yeah no! I had no interest. I preferred my job at the mall because it was fun and I didn’t have to hang out with my parents.  I was a typical teenager.

Civil War history in northern Ohio \nJohnson's Island was a Union prison for Confederate officers during the American Civil War. It was located in Sandusky Bay of Lake Erie, near Sandusky, Ohio. The prison was built on this island for several reasons. Because of the island's isolated location, it would be very difficult for prisoners to escape. At the same time, the island was near several important Ohio cities and lines of road, rail and water transportation. It was relatively easy to acquire building supplies to construct the prison, as well as to secure food to feed the inmates.\nThe Johnson's Island prison was the site for one of the most elaborately planned prison escape attempts of the Civil War.. In Akron Ohio, located on Ardmore Avenue, is Dr. Bob's home, the birthplace of Alcoholics Anonymous.  When you arrive, you are greeted with a firm handshake and a \"Welcome Home.\" There are also 12 steps leading up to Dr. Bob's front door. It is on the national registry of historic places, and is open every day from noon to 3pm due to volunteers with years of sobriety with AA doing the tours. I purposefully did not take pictures inside because I encourage people to see this place of healing and hope yourselves. It was a spiritual experience, one of the most impactful of my life.People in various steps of the program  make a pilgrimage from all over the world (I met people from London) to pay homage and see the home of the man whose program saved their lives. This is Robert Staley or more affectionately known around VVV as "Painter Bob". In the summer of 2017 Painter Bob went from occasional customer to a closest friend knowing all of the most intemate details of our lives, both personally and professionally. Bob spent over 285 hours in the front yard of VVV in pursuit of his free hand painting done "En Plein Air". The painting in its completion now hangs in front of the bar at VVV. To honor Bob's commitment and to recognize our friendship, we are announcing the release of our Pet-Nat formally named En Plein Air. 
There is not a better style of winemaking to highlight this beautiful painting. The back reads, 
EN PLEIN AIR (painting outdoors): Allowing the natural surroundings to break the rules of convention that would otherwise create a predetermined look. 
PETILLANT NATUREL: Risky and Unpredictable. Nothing added, nothing taken away.

It may sound crazy, but I love snow days. Of course I loved them as a child, but I also love them as a mom. ⁣
⁣
It feels like “a pause”⁣
⁣
It’s a day that forces you to stop for one day (or two if you are lucky) and do whatever it is you like at home. ⁣
⁣
When the girls were younger, we used to watch movie after movie under blankets. I didn’t have to drive them anywhere, there were no obligations...just a day to BE. ⁣
⁣
Some days (like today) we play catch up at home. Get some things done that we normally wouldn’t have time for. ⁣
⁣
I really love when nature gives us pause. ⁣
⁣
Like in the summer. I love an occasional rainy day. It forces us to slow down and just be. Regroup, refuel, relax. ⁣
⁣
Hope you were able to enjoy some extra time today ❤️⁣
⁣

This tudor-style house is on the corner of Kiwatha Road and Anoka Lane in Youngstown\u2019s Indian Village Historic District. Indian Village is a small neighborhood on the South Side in between Glenwood Ave. and Mill Creek Park. The neighborhood is suprisingly kept up despite its surroundings and is easily one of Youngstown\u2019s best kept secrets. Kiwatha Rd. in particular is full of these beautiful mansions across the street from Lake Newport. It is even connected to some of Mill Creek Park\u2019s most popular walking and biking trails. As I have spent most of my days near the fresh water ways surrounding Cleveland I am forever grateful for the organizations that were formed after the burning river in ‘69 50yrs ago this year.
The Envirormental organizations such as National Envirormental Policy Act (NEPA) 1970 and Envirormental Protection Agency (EPA) 1972 were put in place by Congress to resolve the issues of land pollution, not just in Cleveland, but throughout the United States. 
One of the first legislations was the Clean Water Act (1972) which mandated that all rivers throughout the United States be hygienic enough to safely allow mass amounts of swimmers and fish within their waters. 
Now, the Cuyahoga river is home to about 60 different species of fish. #tugboat #cuyahoga #river #archives #early2000s"

Our traveling photography & interactive media exhibit is now showing around northeast Ohio! You can see art at the MetroHealth Main Campus, Sunmit Artspace and the Kelvin Smith Library at Case. ⠀
Crooked River Contrasts will travel through communities along the Cuyahoga River in 2019. It will connect the public to the complex history of the river, centered on its rebirth in the 50 years since the infamous 1969 burning.⠀
⠀
All exhibits are free and open to the public. The exhibit features the work of top and emerging Northeast Ohio photographers of the Cuyahoga and Lake Erie watersheds: Ian Adams, Jeffrey Gibson, Jennie Jones, William Rieter, Jim Roetzel and Christina Sadowski. Contrasting their views are images, video and text from noted historical collections covering the 19th, 20th and early 21st centuries.⠀

#CLEVELANDOhio -- A jury awarded a Maple Heights man $22 million this week for a 2012 traffic stop during which he was punched by an East Cleveland police officer and locked in a storage closet for four days without food, water or access to a toilet. 
Arnold Black spent four days alone inside the #EastCleveland Police Headquarters, according to a lawsuit decided this week in #Cuyahoga County Court of Common Pleas, while his family was unable to reach him.
East Cleveland Mayor Gary Norton said Thursday that the city already filed an appeal of the $22 million verdict.

One of the police officers named in the suit, Det. Randy Hicks, testified on behalf of Black after the city filed a lawsuit against him. The detective corroborated the allegations against himself and the department, according to Attorney Rob DiCello.

Oh, you don't know about Poppy, our budget-conscious variation of our Kokosing model?  Oh yea, Poppy's got moves 🕺💃
-
We built Poppy to show an example of what a budget-conscious Kokosing model might look like, and as you can see, it is still a beautiful home.
-
To get the price down, we simply use a few more "functional" materials for the interior design vs. luxury materials, but it doesn't hinder the livability or quality one bit.
-
With that said, we will never cut costs on anything structural, and as an RVIA-builder we always maintain the highest of standards on our foundational bits, like plumbing, electric, frame, trailer, etc. But with a few changes to interior design items, we can build a model with our popular Kokosing design that can fit the majority of budgets!

Attention Everyone:  Say Hello to Clover!

As we mentioned Friday, we just wrapped up Clover, a new 24 ft. Kokosing model for a wonderful young couple from California - and here she is!
.
If you've followed us for a while, you'll notice that Clover looks curiously like another one of our models - The Point!  Actually, Clover is a full Kokosing model, but our customers liked the color scheme and design elements of The Point so much that they requested a Kokosing with the same theme as The Point - and here we are 😍
.
With poplar throughout, concrete countertops, a full gourmet kitchen, full bath, and Modern Tiny Living's popular social area, the Clover is the perfect full time home or travel home.
.

.

Martin Wetzel:
Martin was in the battle of Point Pleasant in 1774. Martin was one of the soldiers who survived the Foreman Massacre near McMechen and was among the defenders of Fort Henry in 1777. Martin, his brother Lewis, and his dad Captain John Wetzel, were also among the defenders in the second attack on Fort Henry on September 11 - 13, 1782, against the British and the Indians, which is known as the last battle of the Revolutionary War. In 1782, Martin and Lewis were among the defenders of Fort Beeler against the Mohawk and Shawnee Indians.

The entire village was lit solely by candlelight and included short vignettes in each building performed by reenactors in period clothing. I wish I had photos to share with you, but flash photography wasn’t allowed and my iPhone wasn’t behaving. If you are in the St. Louis area next weekend, this is a must-see for holiday revelers! 🕯.

Throwback to our first spring in southern Indiana. My daughter and I took our foster dog, Jake, for a hike along German Ridge in the Hoosier National Forest. Along the way, three small puppies approached and followed us for two miles to our vehicle. We loaded them up and stopped at the house nearest to where they\u2019d appeared. A man there said they\u2019d belonged to him, their mother had been killed, and they were in need of homes. I took all three. A rescue group run by a friend took two and we kept the third, the smallest and most timid of the group. We named her Lily. She was 7 in December."
